• The District is closed March 17 through March 30.

• Please email teachers of your building principal with questions you may have regarding alternative learning plans.

Stay safe and healthy.
Mr. Furlow

post_text: The EIU Jazz festival offered an opportunity for high school jazz bands from the region to compete in front of a panel of judges in order to receive constructive feedback. Williamsville earned first place in their class this year, an honor they have received seventeen times in the past nine years at similar festivals across the state. Many individual musicians from the band were recognized for their playing as well. Jack Yearley, Sanjay Mahinda, Chase Webb, Marissa Carrell, and Wyatt Cole were all recognized for their outstanding individual performance, while Jackson Kirkland was awarded for being the “most outstanding” musician of the day. #bulletpride

post_text:
Bullets Basketball to Celebrate 100th Season

Over the past century, the Bullets Basketball Program has been a huge part of the Williamsville and Sherman communities. We invite you to celebrate the rich tradition of Williamsville Bullets Basketball, with the 100th anniversary celebration on Friday, December 20, 2019 against Tri-City. All Former players and coaches in attendance that evening will have the opportunity to be recognized at halftime. Check-in for the recognition ceremony will take place from 5:00-6:30 pm, at Williamsville High School.

Besides the recognition ceremony at halftime, shirts commemorating the 100th season will also be available for purchase from the Williamsville Sports Boosters on December 20. The evening will conclude with a reception at Bella Trattoria in Williamsville. If you have any additional questions regarding this event, you can contact Coach Nick Beard (beard@wcusd15.org) or Athletic Director Adam Eucker (eucker@wcusd15.org).

post_text:
The Williamsville Sports Boosters have been a key organization in the success of the WCUSD 15 Athletic Department by providing a large number of resources to both our coaches and athletes to help them succeed in their respective sports; during the first four months of this school year alone, the booster club has given back over $52,089.50 in requests to both high school and junior high sports. This brings the total to over $377,000 given back to the athletic department over the last six years!

You can continue to help this organization in their support of both Bee Bee and Bullet Athletics by shopping at the annual winter clothing sale. The sale will be taking place on Sunday, December 8 from 11:00 am – 6:00 pm at United Community Bank in Sherman. You can get all of Bullet gear for the holidays, and at the same time ensure the Tradition of Excellence that has been established continues for many years to come.

post_text:
Williamsville High School to Travel to QND for the Semi-finals of 2019 IHSA Playoffs.

The Bullets Football Team has advanced to the semifinals of the IHSA Football Playoffs for the third time in school history. They will travel to Quincy Notre Dame High School this Saturday, November 23, 2019 for a 2:00 pm kickoff. Admission to the game is $8.00. All seating within the stadium is general admission and will be available on a first come first serve basis when gates open at 12:30 pm on Saturday. There is also open seating around the field, and fans can bring lawn chairs with them into the stadium for this purpose.

Currently, the game is not scheduled to be broadcast on WHS Bullets TV. If this changes, additional information will be released.

Please join us as we kickoff Homecoming Week at Williamsville High School on Sunday, September 29, 2019! This will be an evening of fun filled events for both the student body of WHS and the communities of Sherman and Williamsville. We are excited to see everyone that night and once again show why It’s Always Better to be a Bullet as we celebrate Together as One!

Schedule of Events

3:00 pm – Lineup begins for parade at WHS (see attached map for line-up location)

4:00 pm – Parade steps off from WHS (see attached map for parade route)

Approx. 5:00 pm - Pep rally begins at Paul Jenkins Field to include:

- Fall sports parade of athletes
- Cheerleading routine
- Introduction of homecoming court and coronation of king and queen
- Other activities

* The Williamsville Sports Boosters will also be on hand at the pep rally selling both concessions and clothing.

post_text:
Seating at Home Varsity Football Games

In an effort to make the experience more enjoyable for all fans at Bullet Varsity Football games, Williamsville High School does not allow the saving and/or marking of seats prior to the gates opening at Paul Jenkins Field. All seating within the stadium is general admission and will be available on a first come first serve basis when gates open one hour prior to the scheduled kickoff time. Any and all materials placed on the bleachers prior to the opening of the gates on game day will be removed and confiscated. If you have any questions regarding this policy, please contact the athletic department at Williamsville High School.

Five Winter Teams and Activities Earn the IHSA Team Academic Achievement Award

The Williamsville CUSD 15 Athletic Department is proud to announce that all five teams and activities from the 2018-2019 Winter season have been awarded the IHSA Team Academic Achievement Award. This brings the total for the 18-19 school year to twelve teams and activities who have earned this award.

In order to be eligible for this award, a team must have a cumulative GPA of 3.0 or higher. The bar has always been set high at Williamsville High School in terms of success for both academics and athletics. We are proud that this group of student athletes has carried on this tradition of excellence.

Winter

Competitive Cheerleading: 3.54
Boys’ Basketball: 3.61
Music: 3.72

Scholastic Bowl: 4.05

Boys Soccer: 3.39
Football: 3.54

All Seven Fall Varsity Teams Earn the IHSA Team Academic Achievement Award

The Williamsville CUSD 15 Athletic Department is proud to announce, that for the fourth consecutive year, all seven varsity teams from the 2018 Fall season have been awarded the IHSA Team Academic Achievement Award. In order to be eligible for this award, a team must have a cumulative GPA of 3.0 or higher. The overall GPA for the department for the season was 3.67, which was an increase from 3.61 in 2017.

The bar has always been set high at Williamsville High School in terms of success for both academics and athletics. We are proud that this group of student athletes has carried on this tradition of excellence and being all in, all season.

Boys Soccer: 3.39
Football: 3.54
Boys Golf: 3.61
Boys Cross Country: 3.63
Volleyball: 3.80

We’re proud to have been named to the College Board’s 9th Annual AP® District Honor Roll for our efforts to expand access to AP coursework and improve student performance on AP Exams.

post_text:
Cardinals and Bullets Come Together to Help Taylorville.

Pleasant Plains and Williamsville are competitors on the court and the field, but this week they will be partners in the Taylorville tornado relief effort. The gate profit from the high school girls’ basketball game taking place at Pleasant Plains on Thursday, December 6 and the high school boys’ basketball game taking place at Williamsville on Friday, December 7 will be donated to Missions for Taylorville. In addition to these donations from both schools, there will be collection boxes at all home events in both school districts throughout this week where people can donate additional money that will be combined with the gate profit from each game. Both school districts have strong relationships with the Taylorville School District through athletics and want to help the community in their road to recovery. Additional questions regarding these efforts can be directed to Pleasant Plains Athletic Director, Heather Greer, or Williamsville Athletic Director, Adam Eucker.

Bullets Football Team Advances to the Quarterfinals of the Class 3A IHSA State Playoffs

Congratulations to the 2018 Bullets Football Team on advancing to the quarterfinals of the IHSA State Playoffs with a 42-16 win over Fairfield this past Saturday. The Bullets will now travel to Carlinville High School this Saturday, November 10 to take on the Cavaliers. The gates will open at 12:30 pm with kickoff scheduled for 2:00 pm; admission to the game will be $6.00.

There will also be a fan bus provided to the first fifty-five Williamsville High School students to the game on Saturday free of charge. Students can sign up in the main office with Mr. Eucker through the end of school on Wednesday, November 7, 2018.

Williamsville Sports Weekly: Episode 116

In the first episode of the 18-19 school year we take a look back at the Fall sports season and where the teams are heading for the postseason. We also sit down with Superintendent Mr. Reedy to discuss the Sangamon County School Facility Sales Tax that will be on the ballot on Tuesday, November 6. Mr. Reedy gives a detailed breakdown of what the tax is, what will be taxed, and how it would help WCUSD #15. This episode contains a lot of good information so voters can be educated when the go to the voting booth on November 6.

Williamsville High School to Host First Round of 2018 IHSA Playoffs.

Williamsville High School is excited to be hosting the first-round playoff game for the 2018 IHSA Football Playoffs against DuQuoin High School. The game will take place on Saturday, October 27, 2018 at 2:30 pm at Paul Jenkins Field in Williamsville. Admission to the game is $5.00. All seating within the stadium is general admission and will be available on a first come first serve basis when gates open at 1:30 pm on Saturday. Any and all materials placed on the bleachers prior to the opening of the gates on game day will be removed and confiscated.

If you can’t make it to the game, you will be able to watch it live on WHS Bullets TV on the NFHS Network. If you don’t already have a subscription, you will be able to purchase one by going to www.whsbulletstv.com and purchase one of the three passes that are available so you won’t miss a moment of the action during the 2018 playoffs.
